It is generally known that some [underline]weeks[/underline]
[underline]after[/underline] Sir  H Davy's discourses respecting
safety lamps for miners was published it was
Said at Newcastle that a person of
the name of Stephenson had independently
of Sir H Davy invented a lamp upon
upon the same or upon a similar principle
but the claims of this person [deletion][unclear]xxxxxx[/unclear][/deletion] not
being supported either by [deletion]from[/deletion] philosophical or
Common evidence met with no attention
[insertion]from the scientific world[/insertion] till they were brought forward by the
Mess[superscript]s[/superscript] Brandling at Newcastle for the
purpose of robbing Sir H Davy of the
very principle of his discovery, when they
were examined by the president [insertion]of the Royal Society[/insertion] & some
of the most distinguished chemical and philosophical
Men belonging to that Association & likewise
by the great body of the Coal owners of
the Tyne & Weare & not only rejected
[deletion]but accompanied with an opinion[/deletion]
but rejected in a manner which attached
a charge of philosophical piracy to M[superscript]r[/superscript]
George Stephenson; [deletion]the Mess[superscript]s[/superscript] Brandling[/deletion]. A
Committee of M[superscript]r[/superscript] George Stephensons friends
have endeavoured to repel this charge
in a pamphlet to which is annexed
all the evidence in [insertion]his[/insertion] favor [deletion]of M[superscript]r[/superscript] George[/deletion]

